title: The Hancock, N. W. corner St. Nicholas Avenue and One hundred and twenty-fourth Street.

text:
West 124th Street, west from St. Nicholas Avenue. Across the view, behind the gasoline station, are buildings on the west side of Morningside Avenue. Those to the left, at the S. W. corner are owned John D. Rockefeller and will be demolished according to the New York Times article of Oct. 5, 1938. Hancock Place runs in the line of the streetcar tracks in the foreground. The vague structure in the background is the International House.

1: September, 1928
2: September, 1927

George L. Balgue, photo

West 124th Street, west from St. Nicholas Avenue. Across the view, behind the gasoline station, are buildings on the west side of Morningside Avenue. Those to the left, at the S. W. corner are owned John D. Rockefeller and will be demolished according to the New York Times article of Oct. 5, 1938. Hancock Place runs in the line of the streetcar tracks in the foreground. The vague structure in the background is the International House.

1: September, 1928
2: September, 1927

George L. Balgue, photo

W. 124th Street, east from St. Nicholas Avenue. Note the Ninth Avenue Elevated Line running in a north and southward direction on Eighth Avenue. The white building seen at the left is now (1938) gone; having been replaced by a business structure. It bears No. 280 St. Nicholas Avenue and is at the N.E. corner.

July 1929.

Geo. L. Balgue

Manhattan Avenue (left of center) west side, south from Hancock Place (right of center) to W. 123rd Street (extreme left), showing Sydenham Hospital occupying the easterly portion of this block. The photographer is viewing southwestward from the cleared area at the N.E. corner of St. Nicholas Avenue and 124th Street and which is diagonally opposite. To the left is a small area called Hancock Square.

April 1, 1938.

P.L. Sperr

St. Nicholas Avenue, east side, from W. 124th (right) to 125th (left margin) Streets, as viewed in a northeastward direction to show a clearance at the N.E. corner of the first mentioned point. This is of recent occurrence and included a row of 5 story tenements that bore No's. 280 to 286 inclusive and was similar in construction with the 5 unit structure at the left (No's. 332 to 324 West 125th Street). To the right is a row of six, 3 story dwellings (No's. 331 to 321 W. 124th Street) that have individual frontages of 16.8 feet and are midway between St. Nicholas and Eighth Avenues.

March 19, 1938.

P.L. Sperr

St. Nicholas Avenue, west side, from W. 124th (left) to 125th (right) Streets, as viewed northwestward across the cleared area at the N.E. corner of this avenue and 124th Street. The 6 story apartment house is the Hancock Court and the 2 story commercial structure, the Picken Building. To the right of the latter is the 6 story Alpha apartments at the N.W. corner of W. 125th Street and St. Nicholas Avenue.

April 1, 1938.

P.L. Sperr
